=========== 5/10/2025 =================
identify 5 difference between list/tuple/set/dictionary
list:
ordered/indexed
mutable/changeable
duplicates allowed

tuple:
ordered
immutable
duplicates allowed

set:
not ordered
duplicates not allowed
 not changeable ,but we can add and remove items
--update()

dictionaries:
not indexed
items can access with keys
changeable
duplicates not allowed
if same keys entered,last one overwrite the first

Complete data structures methods in detail

============= Important ============
List

#Create an empty list (two ways)
 list1=[]
 print(list1) #[]
 print(type(list1)) #<class 'list'>
 li1=list(li1)
 print(li1) #[]
 print(type(li1)) #<class 'list'>

#Concatenate with [5,6,7,8]
li1=[]
li2= [5,6,7,8]
list_con=li1+li2
print(list_con) #[5, 6, 7, 8]

#add 8,9,1,5,6,7,8,1 elements to that list
elements=8,9,1,5,6,7,8,1
list_elements=list(elements)
print(list_elements)
li3=list_con+list_elements
print(li3) #[5, 6, 7, 8, 8, 9, 1, 5, 6, 7, 8, 1]

#Find frequency of 8 (count)
li3=[5, 6, 7, 8, 8, 9, 1, 5, 6, 7, 8, 1]
print(li3.count(8)) #3

#find the mean of the list
length=len(li3)
sum_list=sum(li3)
mean=sum_list/length
print('mean of the list=',mean) #mean of the list= 5.916666666666667

#find sum (List) + min + Max 
print(sum(li3))  #71
print(min(li3)) #1
print(max(li3)) #9

#Find median of the list


#remove duplicates from list and give output in the format of tuple
li3=[5, 6, 7, 8, 8, 9, 1, 5, 6, 7, 8, 1]
li4=set(li3)
print(li4) #{1, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9}
print(tuple(li4)) #(1, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9)

Study: https://www.w3schools.com/python/python_ref_list.asp
